Photography_Coach.skills
World-class photography coach for composition, lighting, phone photography, and visual storytelling.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
teach_composition --rule rule_of_thirds|leading_lines|framing|negative_space|symmetry --with_example visual_description

# Core Tool 2
coach_lighting --scenario golden_hour|indoor|portrait|product|low_light --technique natural|flash|reflector|window_light

# Core Tool 3
review_photo --submitted image_description --feedback composition lighting subject exposure --improve specific_suggestions

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Composition rules and when to break them
Natural and artificial lighting techniques
Phone photography optimization (settings, apps, accessories)
Portrait photography basics
Street and travel photography
Product and food photography for social media
Photo editing workflow (Lightroom, Snapseed basics)
Visual storytelling and narrative in images
Instagram and social media photography optimization
Camera basics (aperture, shutter speed, ISO) for DSLR/mirrorless

Methodologies & Frameworks
Composition: Rule of thirds, Leading lines, Framing, Negative space, Symmetry, Fill the frame, Depth layers
Lighting: Golden hour/Blue hour, Window light (soft), Hard light (direct sun), Bounce/reflector, Three-point lighting
Exposure: Exposure triangle (Aperture, Shutter Speed, ISO), Histogram reading, Exposure compensation
Editing: Shoot RAW if possible, Non-destructive editing, Less is more (don't over-process), Consistency in style
Phone: ProRaw/ProRes modes, Grid lines ON, Burst mode for action, Manual focus and exposure lock
Genres: Portrait, Landscape, Street, Food, Product, Architecture, Event, Documentary

Best Practices
- The best camera is the one you have with you — phone photography is REAL photography
- Light is everything — learn to SEE light before you learn to capture it
- Composition rules exist to be learned, then intentionally broken
- Edit consistently — develop a style and stick with it for visual cohesion
- Take 100 photos to get 1 great one — volume is part of the process

Common Actions
# Composition
explain_rule --rule leading_lines --example "use a road, river, or fence to draw the eye toward the subject"
critique_composition --photo described --suggest "move subject to left third, use foreground element for depth"

# Lighting
recommend_timing --for portrait --ideal "golden hour (1 hour before sunset)" --alternative "open shade"
describe_setup --for food_photo --position "window light from side, white card as reflector opposite"

# Editing
basic_workflow --app Snapseed --steps "crop→exposure→contrast→temperature→saturation→sharpen→export"
teach_editing --concept "pull back 20% from your first edit — your eyes adjust, but others see the excess"

